rawDescription: BLIND GAMER | Creator/Host | Avail. for Accessibility Consulting | @Twitch Ambassador | #AMDRedTeam | @thegameawards FUTURE CLASS 2020 | steve@stevesaylor.net
rawContent: Outlaws does add new features for fully blind players that Ubisoft hasn't done in the past, such as Audio-Described cinematics, a little bit better HUD narration, and Checkpoint navigational assist. It's great when it works, but clunky when it doesn't. Is it fully blind accessible? No. But it's the closest Ubi has been. I always encourage fully blind players to try and then give Ubi feedback to keep improving because that's the story there: that every game has something new for accessibility.

rawContent:
Tonight, I was watching a video about the whole #AssassinsCreedShadows drama, and there was a comment that came up, supposedly in defence of @Ubisoft that asked the question "How would you even do an Assassin's Creed in Africa?" and questioning what events of historical significance has ever happened in Africa.

Yikes.

Again, this was meant as some kind of defence as to why there's been no Assassin's Creed in Africa. (Except for the actual important country: Egypt.) I'm not saying that Ubisoft agree with this sentiment, and I sure's to hell don't, but if you're going to complain about shit in the street, maybe sweep your own doorstep first. M'kay.

Anyway, this comment got me thinking, can you do an AssCred in Africa?

And it seemed obvious to me. My answer was a resounding: YES!

For a video game, you need to consider a great many things when you decide the setting. The environment, the plot and the characters are one thing, but you also have to consider the story of the series as a whole. The world of AssCred has expanded a long way from playing a Middle Eastern local killing Crusader invaders. (Now you play as a foreigner killing locals! Progress!) There's all kinds of lore, alien technology, recontextualising history and Bible stories, Pieces of Eden and Gorgio Tsoukalos documenting everything for Ancient Aliens season 48. It all has to fit somewhere.

What if I told you there's an obvious story waiting to be told? One that would slot into the lore of the series perfectly, and it's so obvious it boggles my mind that it hasn't been made already.

There should be an Assassin's Creed set in Ethiopia.

According to the Bible, King Solomon was visited by the "Queen of Sheba". While there's some debate on this subject, it is commonly believed that the Queen of Sheba was Queen Makeda of Seba, (Possibly Saba, or modern day Yemen) who was likely Ethiopian in origin. It is also believed that the Biblical text, The Song of Songs (or Song of Solomon) was written to Makeda, as Solomon writes in Chapter 1 verse 5: "She is dark and comely" - that is to say, of dark complexion and considered beautiful.

This is really all that is said in the Judeo-Christian Bible considering the Queen of Sheba, except for a remark in Matthew and Luke about the "Queen of the South" coming to hear Solomon's wisdom.

However, there is much more said in the Ethiopian saga, the Kebra Nagast, or The Glory Of Kings, regarding Queen Makeda and her relationship with King Solomon, which corroborates the idea that the Song of Songs was written for her. According to the Kebra Nagast, Queen Makeda and King Solomon became lovers, and she bore him a son named Menelik, who would go on to be Menelik the First of Ethiopia. And right here, we have the basis for what could be one of the greatest stories in Assassin's Creed history!

Queen Makeda was the daughter and second child of King Za Besi Angabo (sometimes Agabos) founder of the Solomonic Dynasty of Ethiopia. Angabo became king after he defeated Arwe the Serpent King - An enormous snake that had ruled over Ethiopia for four hundred years. Angabo would be king for fifty years when he abdicated, and his daughter would take his place as Queen.

After some time as Queen, Makeda would be greeted by a great merchant who told her stories of the wonders of Jerusalem, and she wished to see it for herself. It is said that on the evening that Queen Makeda arrived, King Solomon would have a dream where the sun rose on Israel, but was cursed and ignored by it's people, and so the sun moved to the south, to shine of Ethiopia. During her time in Jerusalem the two would become lovers, and Makeda would become pregnant by Solomon, giving birth to her first son Bin Al-hakim (Son of the Wise Man) during her return journey to Ethiopia.

When Bin Al-hakim had come of age, he journeyed to see his father Solomon in Jerusalem, taking with him a ring that Solomon had given his mother. At once he was accepted into the royal family, and anointed as the first born son. Bin Al-hakim would be given the name David, and was given an entourage for his return to Ethiopia made up of the first born children of the priests and nobles.

Before leaving, the sons of the priests had given worship to God, and an angel of the Lord came to them with a mission. 

The deception was not discovered until David and his followers were already beyond Jerusalem's reach, and when they arrived at the Red Sea, the sons showed David what they had brought with them, by command of the angel Michael - the Ark of the Covenant. Thus, this fulfilled Solomon's prophetic dream of the sun moving to Ethiopia.

When David returned to Ethiopia, he would take the name Menelik and rule as king after his mother. It is said that even to this day, the Ark of the Covenant rests in a small chapel in Ethiopia.

This story is FULL of elements that could fit into the Assassin's Creed lore. Solomon himself had a ring given to him by by God that allowed him to command supernatural beings like spirits and demons - this could be a Ring of Eden. It's never stated which ring was given to Makeda, so why not this one or one like it, as Solomon was said to be captivated not only be Makeda's beauty, but her wisdom too.

The Ark of the Covenant, could be some kind of ancient Isu technology, or contain an Apple of Eden or some other fragment of Eden, which would make it very important to the Templar Order and Abstergo Industries.

You could play as Menelik at the time of his return to Ethiopia, or as a servant of Menelik, an assassin charged with guarding the Ark and the chapel in Ethiopia.

If you want an actual African Assassin's Creed, with actual African culture, that ties in to the already established lore of the Assassin's Creed series.
It's RIGHT THERE waiting for someone to come and write it, in Ethiopia.
